result.execSummary:
The defendant Kathleen M Henkel was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Theft-Business Setting >$10,000, a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(b).
  • Theft-Business Setting >$10,000, a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(b).
  • Theft-Business Setting >$5000-$10,000, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(b).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Kathleen M Henkel in court with attorney Gary S. Cirilli.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 4:40 PM. State - resolved. Cirilli and Henkel agree - defendant would plead NC to counts #1, #2 and #3 as alleged, #4 - dismissed, #1 - 1 year in FC jail; counts #2 and #3 - withhold sentence and place on probation for 5 years, concurrent to each other but consecutive to the jail time on count #1, restitution as presented to the Court. State - #4 is DRI for restitution purposes. Cirilli and Henkel agree to the amount of restitution but not stipulating to the ability to pay - defendant is going to attempt to pay the restitution. Discussion on court finding that the defendant has the ability to pay the restitution. Recess at 4:46 PM to discuss the matter with the client. Back on record at 4:51 PM. Cirilli makes statement in regards to the restitution and defendant believes she will be able to pay the restitution if ordered. Henkel agrees with what has been stated as far as the plea agreement. Court dismisses and reads in count #4. Henkel pleads NC to counts #1, #2 and #3 as alleged. Court has plea questionnaire, goes thru it, finds the defendant has freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived her constitutional rights and right to JT, accepts plea, adjudges guilty, proceed to sentencing. State makes final argument prior to sentencing - follow joint recommendation - puts restitition amount on record ($103,328.47). Cirilli makes argument prior to sentencing - follow joint recommendation - asks for time to report. State responds - makes statement regarding the restitution/insurance - no objections for delayed time in reporting to jail. Henkel makes statement, remorseful. Court sentences the defendant to the following: count #1 - 1 year in FC jail - huber and good time allowed - eligible for community service under 973.03(3) - report by 4:30 PM on 1/8/16 for stated reasons, costs - paid thru probation on counts #2 and #3; counts #2 and #3 - withhold sentence and place on probation for 5 years, concurrent to each other but consecutive to jail time on count #1, with conditions of: costs on each count - paid thru probation, restitution as submitted - apply bond posted - $30,000.00 of restitution to be paid by noon on 1/7/16 and if not paid - civil judgment entered for that amount and the balance of the restitution to be paid thru probation - credit against restitution for any monies paid by the insurance company, no possession or consumption of alcohol and no entry into any bar or tavern for the purpose of consuming alcohol, 200 hours of community service commencing upon release from incarceration, submit DNA sample, no possession of firearms, no voting rights, right to appeal, adjourned.

Defendant Kathleen M Henkel in court with attorney Gary S. Cirilli.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 2:25 PM. Cirilli - just received offer from the State today, asking that the matter be set for another FPT. State agrees - lots of accounting needed as there is alot of restitution requested - State still holding offer open. Court continues bond, considers it not resolved and does not have to hold open the offer, sets for JT. If resolved prior, can schedule a FPT with JA. Any motions need to be filed 10 days prior to JT and possibly heard 5 days prior to JT.  Jury trial scheduled for January 7, 2016 at 08:30 am.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Kathleen M Henkel in court with attorney Gary S. Cirilli.  Jodie L. Bednar appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 2:08 PM. Cirilli has complaint, waives reading of it, requests PH but will waive time limits. Court considers time limits waived, set for PH. Cirilli - bond - asks for reduction in bond for stated reasons ($2500.00 cash). State - bond - objects to bond reduction for stated reasons - also asks that the court add conditions of no consumption of alcohol and no entry into any bars or taverns. Cirilli objects to the additional bond conditions in regards to entering into a bar or tavern that serves food. Court responds. Court - bond - amends bond to $2500.00 cash with no consumption of alcohol, refund remaining $2500.00 to poster.  Preliminary hearing scheduled for August 3, 2015 at 01:30 pm.
